text: <p>I think that the lizards start moving from island C to the next closest islands, A and D, then move in between them. Then I think they move to the next closest islands, B and E, and start moving between them as well. I think that floating logs or debris may be responsible for the dispersal patterns, or human movement. </p>

<p>You wouldn't be able to tell which dispersal event occurred first when comparing island A and D together and island B and C, but i said that the dispersal event to island D occurred first just because island D looks closer to C than A</p>

<p>The ancestral population existed on island C; first moved to D because it is the closest relative to C. New species evolves at D, then disperses to E and A, creating new species on each respectively. E is too far from B, so colonists from A end up on island B instead, thus explaining the branch in the tree. I believe proximity has the most to do with the dispersal patterns.</p>

<p>Based on the phylogenetic tree, I think that the first event went to island D because of how it broke off from C and proximity, then flowed to E at the same time more lizards went to A and then those lizards were able to travel to B.</p>

<p>The lizards on island C may have dispersed to islands D and A at around the same time because they were the closest islands to C. The lizards on D jumped to island E because it was the next closest island and the tree shows that the lizards on those two islands are closely related. The same goes for the lizards on islands A and B.</p>

<p>Islands A and B, and E and D dispersed away from ancestral island C at the relatively same time indicated by the phylogenetic tree, and some factors that caused the dispersals could be the ancestral population was outcompeting the others, or the lizards colonized the other islands when humans did aboard their ships.</p>
<p>Some factors that might be responsible for dispersal would be resources, less competition, and the quality of the habitat.</p>

<p>It is possible that large storm events caused some lizards to be swept away on logs or other debris (jump dispersal) onto other islands, ultimately leading to allopatric speciation. Or it may be possible that humans dispersed the lizards onto other islands (jump dispersal).</p>
